ChatGPT said:

Sure ‚Äî here‚Äôs the simplified DeploymentConfig using the full registry path for the httpd image, without any PVC (so no persistent storage).

This version uses an ephemeral emptyDir volume, which is recreated fresh each time the Pod restarts ‚Äî ideal for lightweight, temporary deployments.

‚úÖ DeploymentConfig using full registry path (no PVC)
apiVersion: apps.openshift.io/v1
kind: DeploymentConfig
metadata:
  name: httpd-sample
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    app: httpd-sample
  strategy:
    type: Rolling
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: httpd-sample
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: httpd
        image: docker.io/library/httpd:2.4
        imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
          protocol: TCP
        volumeMounts:
        - name: web-content
          mountPath: /usr/local/apache2/htdocs
      volumes:
      - name: web-content
        emptyDir: {}
  triggers:
  - type: ConfigChange

üîç Explanation

image: docker.io/library/httpd:2.4 ‚Üí full registry path to the official Apache HTTPD image.

emptyDir: {} ‚Üí creates a temporary volume inside the pod.

Content will be deleted when the pod restarts or redeploys.

mountPath: /usr/local/apache2/htdocs ‚Üí this is where httpd serves content from.

No PVC or storage configuration ‚Üí simplifies setup; suitable for testing or static content baked into the image.

üåê Optional: expose service and route
oc expose dc/httpd-sample --port=80 --name=httpd-service
oc expose svc/httpd-service


This will give you a route URL to access the server externally.

Would you like me to modify this version to serve content from a ConfigMap instead (for static HTML files), so it can show a custom page instead of the default Apache index?
